Prior research has primarily studied clinical dialogue summarization in monolingual settings, focusing on structured note generation, while the problem of trustworthiness in cross-lingual clinical summarization remains largely unexplored.
\citet{lyu2025automatic} use prompt-tuned clinical LLMs to summarize doctor–patient dialogues into structured notes, demonstrating strong performance on MTS-DIALOG.
While recent advances in large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated promising performance in medical summarization tasks, the vast majority of existing work focuses on English-only settings.
However, real-world clinical communication spans diverse languages, and healthcare delivery frequently occurs in multilingual and low-resource linguistic environments. In this paper, we analyze the trustworthiness of cross-lingual clinical summarization systems, focusing on trustworthiness, safety, and explainability. We examine how linguistic and resource differences influence summarization quality and demonstrate that performance degrades substantially for low-resource languages. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first systematic study that characterizes trustworthiness failures in multilingual clinical dialogue summarization for Indic languages. These results underscore the need for linguistically informed, safety-aware evaluation frameworks for multilingual clinical NLP.
